08706nam a22009135i 9781787444805DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874448057 a10.1515/97817874448052doi  a(DE-B1597)675320  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a623.4/4104aThe Sword :bForm and Thought /ced. by Mirjam Kaiser, Sixt Wetzler, Lisa Deutscher. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (294 p.) :b90 colour, 27 b/w, 23 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArmour and Weapons ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tList of Contributors -- tI Typology -- t1 “What is the Riddle of Steel?”: Problems of Classification and Terminology in the Study of Late Medieval Swords -- t2 Challenging Typologies: Swords in the Utrecht Psalter -- t3 “… schirmen mit Federklingen”: Towards a Terminology of Fencing Swords (1400–1600) -- tII Metallurgy and Production -- t4 Phosphoric Iron and Welded Patterns: The Reconstruction of an Early Medieval Sword from Beckum -- t5 Material and Properties of VLFBERHT Swords -- t6 A Sword from the Rhine: Restoration, Examination and Classification of a Chance Find -- t7 The Highest Art of Smithery: Research on a Tyrolean Sword -- tIII Symbolic Meaning and Cultural Perception -- t8 The Battle for Glory: Form and Function of Early Nordic Bronze Age Swords -- t9 The Iron Sword from the “Warrior’s Grave” in Lanuvium -- t10 The Swords of the Italic Kings -- t11 Three Treasures in One Blade: Thoughts on a Rare Form of the Japanese Sword -- t12 “.j. veel feble fauchon dil anxien temps.” The Selection of the Falchion as Symbol of Tenure: Form, Function and Symbolism -- t13 The Way of the Northmen: The Development of the Norman Sword from Duke Rollo in Normandy to Emperor Frederick II in Sicily from the Tenth to the Thirteenth Century -- tIV Fighting and Swordsmanship -- t14 Researching Bronze Age Swordsmanship: Experiments and Wear Analysis -- t15 Egenolff ’s Fight Book: Form and Thought, Then and Now -- t16 A Sword for a System: The Pattern 1796 Light Cavalry Sword -- tBibliography -- tIndex of People -- tIndex of Places -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA multidisciplinary overview of current research into the enduringly fascinating martial artefact which is the sword.The sword is the most iconic of all weapons. Throughout history, it has connected various, sometimes conflicting, dimensions of human culture: physical combat and representation of political power, definition of gender roles andrefinement of body techniques, evolution of craftsmanship and mythological symbolism. The articles collected here explore these dimensions, from a variety of disciplines, among them archaeology, medieval history, museum conservation, and linguistics. They cover topics from the production and combat use of Bronze Age swords via medieval fencing culture to the employment of the sword in modern military. They question traditional sword typologies and wide-spread theories about sword making, discuss medieval sword terminology and the use of swords as royal insignia, and describe the scientific methods for approaching original finds. Arising from an international conference held atDeutsches Klingenmuseum Solingen (the German Blade Museum), the volume provides fresh insights into the forms the sword can take, and the thoughts it inspires. LISA DEUTSCHER and MIRJAM E. KAISER work in prehistoric archaeology, specialising in La Tène and Bronze Age swords, respectively. SIXT WETZLER is the deputy director of the German Blade Museum; his research focuses on the history of edged weapons, and their use. Contributors:Matthias Johannes Bauer, Holger Becker, Jan-Heinrich Bunnefeld, Rach